# Accessibility Audit Checklist

## Visual Design

### Color and Contrast
- [ ] All text has minimum 4.5:1 contrast ratio (WCAG AA)
- [ ] Large text (18pt+) has minimum 3:1 contrast ratio
- [ ] Color is not the only means of conveying information
- [ ] Passes color blindness simulation tests
- [ ] Sufficient contrast for UI components (buttons, form fields)

### Typography
- [ ] Text is resizable up to 200% without loss of content
- [ ] Text reflows without horizontal scrolling at 320px width
- [ ] No text justified (left or right only)
- [ ] Sufficient spacing between lines and paragraphs

## Keyboard Navigation

### Focus Management
- [ ] All interactive elements are keyboard accessible
- [ ] Focus order follows logical sequence
- [ ] Focus indicators are visible and clear
- [ ] No keyboard traps exist
- [ ] Skip links are provided for main content

### Keyboard Interactions
- [ ] All functionality is operable via keyboard
- [ ] Standard keyboard shortcuts are followed
- [ ] Custom keyboard interactions are documented
- [ ] Modal dialogs trap focus while open
- [ ] Focus returns to appropriate location after actions

## Screen Reader Compatibility

### Semantic HTML
- [ ] Proper heading hierarchy (h1, h2, h3, etc.) is maintained
- [ ] Headings describe section content accurately
- [ ] Lists use proper list elements (ul, ol, dl)
- [ ] Tables use proper structure (th, scope, caption)
- [ ] Landmarks are used appropriately (nav, main, aside, etc.)

### Alternative Text
- [ ] All informative images have descriptive alt text
- [ ] Decorative images have empty alt text (alt="")
- [ ] Complex images have detailed descriptions
- [ ] Images of text have alt text matching the text
- [ ] CAPTCHA images have non-visual alternatives

### ARIA Implementation
- [ ] ARIA labels are used when semantic HTML is insufficient
- [ ] ARIA landmarks are used to improve navigation
- [ ] Live regions are used for dynamic content updates
- [ ] ARIA roles are used appropriately and correctly
- [ ] ARIA attributes have proper values and relationships

## Forms and Input

### Labels and Instructions
- [ ] All form fields have associated labels
- [ ] Labels are descriptive and clear
- [ ] Instructions are provided for complex inputs
- [ ] Error messages are clear and descriptive
- [ ] Required fields are clearly identified

### Error Handling
- [ ] Error messages identify the problem clearly
- [ ] Error messages suggest how to fix the problem
- [ ] Error notifications are programmatically determinable
- [ ] Focus moves to first error after submission
- [ ] Data is preserved when errors occur

## Media and Content

### Audio and Video
- [ ] Audio content has transcripts available
- [ ] Video content has captions
- [ ] Audio does not autoplay or has controls
- [ ] Video content has audio description if needed
- [ ] Media players have keyboard controls

### Links and Navigation
- [ ] Link text describes the destination or action
- [ ] Link purpose is clear from context or programmatically determinable
- [ ] Sufficient space between links for touch/mouse users
- [ ] Navigation is consistent across pages
- [ ] Breadcrumb navigation is provided for multi-level sites

## Mobile and Touch

### Touch Targets
- [ ] All touch targets are at least 44px by 44px
- [ ] Adequate spacing between touch targets
- [ ] Touch targets are not clustered
- [ ] Touch gestures have mouse alternatives
- [ ] Touch actions can be canceled when appropriate

### Orientation and Zoom
- [ ] Content is usable in both portrait and landscape
- [ ] Horizontal scrolling is not required at 320px width
- [ ] Text scales appropriately up to 200%
- [ ] Viewport is not locked to prevent zooming
- [ ] Content is not cut off when zoomed

## Testing and Validation

### Automated Testing
- [ ] Run accessibility testing tools (axe, WAVE, etc.)
- [ ] Validate HTML markup
- [ ] Check color contrast ratios
- [ ] Test with automated accessibility checkers
- [ ] Review results and fix identified issues

### Manual Testing
- [ ] Test with keyboard only
- [ ] Test with screen reader (NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver)
- [ ] Test with reduced motion settings
- [ ] Test with high contrast mode
- [ ] Test with different browsers and devices

### User Testing
- [ ] Include users with disabilities in testing
- [ ] Test with assistive technology users
- [ ] Gather feedback on accessibility features
- [ ] Validate that accessibility features work as intended
- [ ] Document any user feedback or issues

## Platform Specific

### Web Applications
- [ ] ARIA attributes are used appropriately for dynamic content
- [ ] Focus management is handled for single-page applications
- [ ] Dynamic content updates are announced to screen readers
- [ ] Modal dialogs are properly implemented
- [ ] Custom controls have proper keyboard support

### Mobile Applications
- [ ] VoiceOver/TalkBack compatibility is tested
- [ ] Dynamic Type/Sizes are supported where applicable
- [ ] Touch target sizes meet minimum requirements
- [ ] Appropriate accessibility attributes are implemented
- [ ] Platform accessibility guidelines are followed

## Documentation

### Accessibility Statement
- [ ] Accessibility statement is available and up-to-date
- [ ] Known limitations are documented
- [ ] Contact information for accessibility feedback is provided
- [ ] Commitment to accessibility is stated
- [ ] Testing methods and results are documented

### Development Guidelines
- [ ] Accessibility requirements are documented
- [ ] Development team is trained on accessibility
- [ ] Accessibility is included in design process
- [ ] Testing procedures include accessibility checks
- [ ] Remediation processes are established